WEBVTT

00:25.740 --> 00:28.540
CHAPTER V.

00:28.540 --> 00:30.220
Anne's History

00:58.620 --> 00:59.860
Isn't it lovely?

01:00.700 --> 01:03.380
Don't you think it must be glad to be a rose?

01:04.020 --> 01:05.900
Wouldn't it be nice if roses could talk?

01:06.320 --> 01:08.960
I'm sure they could tell us such lovely things.

01:09.420 --> 01:12.540
And isn't pink the most bewitching colour in the world?

01:13.060 --> 01:15.400
I love it, but I can't wear it.

01:15.920 --> 01:19.600
Red-headed people can't wear pink, not even in imagination.

01:20.440 --> 01:24.200
Did you ever know of anybody whose hair was red when she was young,

01:24.640 --> 01:27.020
but got to be another colour when she grew up?

01:27.020 --> 01:32.980
No, I don't know as I ever did, said Marilla mercilessly,

01:33.240 --> 01:36.700
and I shouldn't think it likely to happen in your case either.

01:38.320 --> 01:39.280
Anne sighed.

01:39.760 --> 01:42.360
Well, that is another hope gone.

01:42.980 --> 01:46.520
My life is a perfect graveyard of buried hopes.

01:47.160 --> 01:49.240
That's a sentence I read in a book once,

01:49.540 --> 01:53.840
and I say it over to comfort myself whenever I'm disappointed in anything.

01:53.840 --> 01:58.760
I don't see where the comforting comes in myself, said Marilla.

01:59.300 --> 02:01.940
Why, because it sounds so nice and romantic,

02:02.380 --> 02:04.860
just as if I were a heroine in a book, you know.

02:05.260 --> 02:07.380
I am so fond of romantic things,

02:07.740 --> 02:14.020
and a graveyard full of buried hopes is about as romantic a thing as one can imagine, isn't it?

02:14.580 --> 02:16.240
I'm rather glad I have one.

02:16.780 --> 02:19.460
Are we going across the Lake of Shining Waters today?

02:20.200 --> 02:22.560
We're not going over Barry's pond,

02:22.620 --> 02:25.580
if that's what you mean by your Lake of Shining Waters.

02:26.080 --> 02:27.620
We're going by the Shore Road.

02:28.680 --> 02:32.100
Shore Road sounds nice, said Anne dreamily.

02:32.680 --> 02:34.280
Is it as nice as it sounds?

02:34.940 --> 02:37.260
Just when you said Shore Road,

02:37.680 --> 02:40.800
I saw it in a picture in my mind as quick as that,

02:41.400 --> 02:43.880
and White Sands is a pretty name too,

02:44.200 --> 02:46.880
but I don't like it as well as Avonlea.

02:46.880 --> 02:49.320
Avonlea is a lovely name.

02:49.680 --> 02:51.500
It just sounds like music.

02:52.200 --> 02:54.460
How far is it to White Sands?

02:55.380 --> 02:56.680
It's five miles,

02:56.980 --> 02:59.340
and as you're evidently bent on talking,

02:59.640 --> 03:01.860
you might as well talk to some purpose

03:01.860 --> 03:04.380
by telling me what you know about yourself.

03:05.540 --> 03:08.800
Oh, what I know about myself isn't really worth telling,

03:09.280 --> 03:10.180
said Anne eagerly.

03:10.380 --> 03:13.940
If you'll only let me tell you what I imagine about myself,

03:13.940 --> 03:16.700
you'll think it ever so much more interesting.

03:17.700 --> 03:20.220
No, I don't want any of your imaginings.

03:20.980 --> 03:22.940
Just you stick to bald facts.

03:23.460 --> 03:24.760
Begin at the beginning.

03:25.380 --> 03:27.860
Where were you born, and how old are you?

03:28.820 --> 03:31.580
I was eleven last March, said Anne,

03:31.820 --> 03:34.720
resigning herself to bald facts with a little sigh,

03:34.840 --> 03:38.120
and I was born in Bolingbroke, Nova Scotia.

03:39.020 --> 03:41.120
My father's name was Walter Shirley,

03:41.120 --> 03:44.540
and he was a teacher in the Bolingbroke High School.

03:45.480 --> 03:47.200
My mother's name was Bertha Shirley.

03:47.880 --> 03:50.560
Aren't Walter and Bertha lovely names?

03:51.120 --> 03:53.520
I'm so glad my parents had nice names.

03:54.080 --> 03:56.620
It would be a real disgrace to have a father named,

03:57.000 --> 04:00.100
well, say, Jedidiah, wouldn't it?

04:00.680 --> 04:03.660
I guess it doesn't matter what a person's name is

04:03.660 --> 04:06.960
as long as he behaves himself, said Marilla,

04:07.340 --> 04:08.980
feeling herself called upon

04:08.980 --> 04:12.060
to inculcate a good and useful moral.

04:12.980 --> 04:16.000
Well, I don't know, Anne looked thoughtful.

04:16.640 --> 04:20.260
I read in a book once that a rose by any other name

04:20.260 --> 04:21.600
would smell as sweet,

04:22.120 --> 04:24.340
but I've never been able to believe it.

04:24.580 --> 04:26.840
I don't believe a rose would be as nice

04:26.840 --> 04:30.040
if it was called a thistle or a skunk cabbage.

04:30.860 --> 04:34.380
I suppose my father could have been a good man,

04:34.420 --> 04:36.800
even if he had been called Jedidiah,

04:36.800 --> 04:38.880
but I'm sure it would have been a cross.

04:39.800 --> 04:42.860
Well, my mother was a teacher in the high school, too,

04:43.120 --> 04:45.840
but when she married father she gave up teaching, of course.

04:46.360 --> 04:48.240
A husband was enough responsibility.

04:49.200 --> 04:51.840
Mrs. Thomas said that they were a pair of babies

04:51.840 --> 04:53.620
and as poor as church mice.

04:54.260 --> 04:56.160
They went to live in a weeny-teeny

04:56.160 --> 04:58.220
little yellow house in Bolingbroke.

04:58.540 --> 04:59.960
I've never seen that house,

05:00.000 --> 05:02.200
but I've imagined it thousands of times.

05:02.680 --> 05:04.500
I think it must have had honeysuckle

05:04.500 --> 05:08.180
over the parlor window and lilacs in the front yard

05:08.180 --> 05:11.060
and lilies of the valley just inside the gate.

05:11.680 --> 05:14.420
Yes, and muslin curtains in all the windows.

05:15.000 --> 05:17.580
Muslin curtains give a house such an air.

05:18.120 --> 05:19.620
I was born in that house.

05:20.120 --> 05:23.400
Mrs. Thomas said I was the homeliest baby she ever saw.

05:23.720 --> 05:26.940
I was so scrawny and tiny and nothing but eyes,

05:27.180 --> 05:29.760
but that mother thought I was perfectly beautiful.

05:30.380 --> 05:32.780
I should think a mother would be a better judge

05:32.780 --> 05:35.940
than a poor woman who came into scrub, wouldn't you?

05:36.660 --> 05:39.100
I'm glad she was satisfied with me anyhow.

05:39.660 --> 05:42.780
I would feel so sad if I thought I was a disappointment to her,

05:43.120 --> 05:45.740
because she didn't live very long after that, you see.

05:46.040 --> 05:48.860
She died of fever when I was just three months old.

05:49.440 --> 05:51.500
I do wish she'd lived long enough

05:51.500 --> 05:53.280
for me to remember calling her mother.

05:53.860 --> 05:55.660
I think it would be so sweet to say,

05:55.940 --> 05:57.540
Mother, don't you?

05:58.280 --> 06:01.620
And father died four days afterwards from fever, too.

06:02.180 --> 06:05.780
That left me an orphan, and folks were at their wits end,

06:06.020 --> 06:08.640
so Mrs. Thomas said what to do with me.

06:09.260 --> 06:11.740
You see, nobody wanted me even then.

06:12.260 --> 06:13.660
It seems to be my fate.

06:14.380 --> 06:17.880
Father and mother had both come from places far away,

06:18.220 --> 06:21.240
and it was well known they hadn't any relatives living.

06:22.140 --> 06:25.060
Finally, Mrs. Thomas said she'd take me,

06:25.200 --> 06:27.680
though she was poor and had a drunken husband.

06:28.120 --> 06:29.780
She brought me up by hand.

06:29.780 --> 06:33.340
Do you know if there's anything in being brought up by hand

06:33.340 --> 06:35.840
that ought to make people who were brought up that way

06:35.840 --> 06:37.320
better than other people?

06:37.920 --> 06:39.400
Because whenever I was naughty,

06:39.940 --> 06:42.860
Mrs. Thomas would ask me how I could be such a bad girl

06:42.860 --> 06:46.460
when she had brought me up by hand, reproachful-like.

06:47.600 --> 06:50.920
Mr. and Mrs. Thomas moved away from Bolingbrook to Marysville,

06:51.280 --> 06:54.180
and I lived with them until I was eight years old.

06:54.640 --> 06:56.660
I helped look after the Thomas children.

06:56.880 --> 06:58.780
There were four of them younger than me,

06:58.780 --> 07:02.140
and I can tell you they took a lot of looking after.

07:02.900 --> 07:05.880
Then Mr. Thomas was killed falling under a train,

07:06.440 --> 07:09.340
and his mother offered to take Mrs. Thomas and the children,

07:09.740 --> 07:11.280
but she didn't want me.

07:11.940 --> 07:14.120
Mrs. Thomas was at her wits' end,

07:14.240 --> 07:16.380
so she said what to do with me.

07:17.260 --> 07:21.140
Then Mrs. Hammond from up the river came down and said she'd take me,

07:21.440 --> 07:23.180
seeing I was handy with children,

07:23.500 --> 07:25.640
and I went up the river to live with her

07:25.640 --> 07:27.620
in a little clearing among the stumps.

07:27.620 --> 07:30.020
It was a very lonesome place.

07:30.420 --> 07:33.980
I'm sure I could never have lived there if I hadn't had an imagination.

07:35.520 --> 07:38.060
Mr. Hammond worked a little sawmill up there,

07:38.440 --> 07:40.260
and Mrs. Hammond had eight children.

07:40.880 --> 07:42.860
She had twins three times.

07:43.500 --> 07:45.340
I like babies in moderation,

07:45.720 --> 07:49.540
but twins three times in succession is too much.

07:50.180 --> 07:54.100
I told Mrs. Hammond so firmly when the last pair came.

07:54.100 --> 07:58.080
I used to get so dreadfully tired carrying them about.

07:59.100 --> 08:02.020
I lived upriver with Mrs. Hammond over two years,

08:02.480 --> 08:04.020
and then Mr. Hammond died,

08:04.240 --> 08:06.060
and Mrs. Hammond broke up housekeeping.

08:06.780 --> 08:10.280
She divided her children among her relatives and went to the States.

08:10.960 --> 08:15.280
I had to go to the asylum at Hopeton because nobody would take me.

08:15.840 --> 08:17.880
They didn't want me at the asylum either.

08:18.220 --> 08:20.300
They said they were overcrowded as it was,

08:20.740 --> 08:22.160
but they had to take me,

08:22.160 --> 08:25.440
and I was there four months until Mrs. Spencer came.

08:26.360 --> 08:29.780
Anne finished up with another sigh of relief this time.

08:30.480 --> 08:33.420
Evidently, she did not like talking about her experiences

08:33.420 --> 08:35.940
in a world that had not wanted her.

08:36.720 --> 08:38.440
Did you ever go to school?

08:38.860 --> 08:42.760
demanded Marilla, turning the sorrel mare down the shore road.

08:43.640 --> 08:44.780
Not a great deal.

08:44.900 --> 08:47.960
I went a little the last year I stayed with Mrs. Thomas.

08:48.480 --> 08:51.380
When I went upriver we were so far from a school

08:51.380 --> 08:53.440
that I couldn't walk it in winter,

08:53.920 --> 08:55.680
and there was a vacation in summer,

08:55.740 --> 08:57.780
so I could only go in the spring and fall.

08:58.340 --> 09:00.740
But of course I went while I was at the asylum.

09:01.360 --> 09:02.560
I can read pretty well,

09:02.700 --> 09:05.640
and I know ever so many pieces of poetry by heart.

09:06.420 --> 09:07.380
The Battle of Hohenlinden,

09:08.500 --> 09:10.360
and Edinburgh after Flodden,

09:10.920 --> 09:12.560
and Bingen of the Rhine,

09:12.780 --> 09:14.380
and lots of The Lady of the Lake,

09:14.880 --> 09:17.440
and most of The Seasons by James Thompson.

09:18.160 --> 09:19.560
Don't you just love poetry

09:19.560 --> 09:22.440
that gives you a crinkly feeling up and down your back?

09:23.620 --> 09:25.440
There is a piece in the fifth reader,

09:25.900 --> 09:27.360
The Downfall of Poland,

09:27.780 --> 09:29.680
that is just full of thrills.

09:30.200 --> 09:32.040
Of course I wasn't in the fifth reader.

09:32.220 --> 09:33.540
I was only in the fourth.

09:34.040 --> 09:36.420
But the big girls used to lend me theirs to read.

09:37.640 --> 09:41.740
Were those women, Mrs. Thomas and Mrs. Hammond, good to you?

09:41.980 --> 09:45.080
asked Marilla, looking at Anne out of the corner of her eye.

09:46.280 --> 09:47.980
Oh, faltered Anne.

09:47.980 --> 09:51.840
Her sensitive little face suddenly flushed scarlet,

09:52.200 --> 09:54.140
and embarrassment sat on her brow.

09:55.080 --> 09:56.600
Oh, they meant to be.

09:56.720 --> 09:59.800
I know they meant to be just as good and kind as possible.

10:00.380 --> 10:02.420
And when people mean to be good to you,

10:02.640 --> 10:05.680
you don't mind very much when they're not quite, always.

10:06.220 --> 10:08.400
They had a good deal to worry them, you know.

10:08.680 --> 10:11.820
It's very trying to have a drunken husband, you see.

10:12.080 --> 10:14.460
And it must be very trying to have twins

10:14.460 --> 10:16.660
three times in succession, don't you think?

10:16.660 --> 10:19.780
But I feel sure they meant to be good to me.

10:20.740 --> 10:22.480
Marilla asked no more questions.

10:23.120 --> 10:27.060
Anne gave herself up to a silent rapture over the shore road,

10:27.660 --> 10:32.100
and Marilla guided the sorrel abstractedly while she pondered deeply.

10:33.160 --> 10:36.100
Pity was suddenly stirring in her heart for the child.

10:36.740 --> 10:39.520
What a starved, unloved life she had led.

10:40.000 --> 10:43.480
A life of drudgery and poverty and neglect.

10:43.480 --> 10:48.280
For Marilla was shrewd enough to read between the lines of Anne's history

10:48.280 --> 10:50.100
and divine the truth.

10:50.860 --> 10:54.780
No wonder she had been so delighted at the prospect of a real home.

10:55.720 --> 10:58.180
It was a pity she had to be sent back.

10:58.960 --> 11:02.980
What if she, Marilla, should indulge Matthew's unaccountable whim

11:02.980 --> 11:03.960
and let her stay?

11:04.860 --> 11:08.880
He was set on it, and the child seemed a nice, teachable little thing.

11:09.700 --> 11:12.740
She's got too much to say, thought Marilla,

11:13.080 --> 11:14.880
but she might be trained out of that,

11:15.200 --> 11:18.520
and there's nothing rude or slangy in what she does say.

11:18.960 --> 11:22.380
She's ladylike. It's likely her people were nice folks.

11:23.260 --> 11:27.080
The shore road was woodsy and wild and lonesome.

11:27.600 --> 11:30.140
On the right hand scrubbed firs,

11:30.340 --> 11:35.000
their spirits, quite unbroken by long years of tussle with the gulf winds,

11:35.520 --> 11:36.620
grew thickly.

11:36.620 --> 11:40.980
On the left were the steep red sandstone cliffs,

11:41.520 --> 11:46.660
so near the tracking places that a mare of less steadiness than the sorrel

11:46.660 --> 11:49.580
might have tried the nerves of the people behind her.

11:50.380 --> 11:56.600
Down at the base of the cliffs were heaps of surf-worn rocks or little sandy coves,

11:56.880 --> 11:59.400
inlaid with pebbles as with ocean jewels.

11:59.880 --> 12:03.400
Beyond lay the sea, shimmering and blue,

12:03.400 --> 12:09.320
and over it soared the gulls, their pinions flashing silvery in the sunlight.

12:10.760 --> 12:16.600
Isn't the sea wonderful? said Anne, rousing from a long, wide-eyed silence.

12:17.240 --> 12:21.780
Once, when I lived in Marysville, Mr. Thomas hired an express wagon

12:21.780 --> 12:25.920
and took us all to spend the day at the shore ten miles away.

12:26.420 --> 12:32.200
I enjoyed every moment of that day, even if I had to look after the children all the time.

12:32.200 --> 12:35.800
I lived it over in happy dreams for years,

12:36.320 --> 12:39.300
but this shore is nicer than the Marysville shore.

12:39.820 --> 12:41.480
Aren't those gulls splendid?

12:42.140 --> 12:43.520
Would you like to be a gull?

12:43.720 --> 12:47.380
I think I would, that is, if I couldn't be a human girl.

12:48.180 --> 12:53.200
Don't you think it would be nice to wake up at sunrise and swoop down over the water

12:53.200 --> 12:56.680
and away out over that lovely blue all day,

12:56.980 --> 12:59.780
and then at night to fly back to one's nest?

12:59.780 --> 13:02.940
Oh, I can just imagine myself doing it.

13:03.720 --> 13:06.180
What big house is that just ahead, please?

13:07.380 --> 13:09.320
That's the White Sands Hotel.

13:09.900 --> 13:13.260
Mr. Kirk runs it, but the season hasn't begun yet.

13:13.760 --> 13:16.640
There are heaps of Americans come there for the summer.

13:17.120 --> 13:19.720
They think this shore is just about right.

13:20.600 --> 13:24.820
I was afraid it might be Mrs. Spencer's place, said Anne mournfully.

13:25.220 --> 13:26.720
I don't want to get there.

13:26.720 --> 13:30.060
Somehow it will seem like the end of everything.

13:32.420 --> 13:34.300
End of chapter five.

